### Getters and Setters in C#

Properties use `get` and `set` accessors to control how values are read and written.

### Get Accessor

Returns the property value. Can contain any logic:

```csharp
private int temperature;

public int Temperature
{
    get
    {
        // Custom logic when reading
        Console.WriteLine($"Temperature was read: {temperature}");
        return temperature;
    }
}
```

### Set Accessor

Assigns a value using the implicit `value` parameter:

```csharp
public int Temperature
{
    set
    {
        // 'value' is the assigned value
        if (value < -273)
            throw new ArgumentException("Below absolute zero");
        temperature = value;
    }
}
```

### Access Modifiers on Accessors

Different accessibility for get and set:

```csharp
public string Name
{
    get { return name; }
    private set { name = value; }  // Only the class can set
}

public int Id { get; private set; }
public string Email { get; init; }  // Init-only setter (C# 9+)
```

### Expression-Bodied Accessors (C# 6+)

```csharp
private string name;

public string Name
{
    get => name;
    set => name = value ?? "Unknown";
}
```

### Get-Only Auto-Property with Constructor

```csharp
public class Person
{
    public string Name { get; }

    public Person(string name)
    {
        Name = name;  // Can set in constructor only
    }
}
```

### Init-Only Setters (C# 9+)

```csharp
public class WeatherData
{
    public double Temperature { get; init; }
    public double Humidity { get; init; }
}

// Can only be set during object initialization
var data = new WeatherData
{
    Temperature = 25.5,
    Humidity = 0.6
};
// data.Temperature = 30;  // Error - init only
```

### Required with Init (C# 11+)

```csharp
public class Product
{
    public required string Name { get; init; }
    public required decimal Price { get; init; }
}
```

### Getter/Setter Combinations

| Pattern | Get | Set | Use Case |
|---------|-----|-----|----------|
| Read/write | public | public | Standard mutable property |
| Read-only | public | private | Controlled mutation |
| Write-only | private | public | Rare, mostly for setters |
| Init-only | public | init | Immutable after init |
| Computed | expression | none | Derived values |

> **Key Point:** The `value` keyword in a setter represents the assigned value. Use `init` for properties that should be immutable after object creation. `required` ensures callers provide the value during initialization.

### Property Change Notification

```csharp
private string name;
public string Name
{
    get => name;
    set
    {
        if (name != value)
        {
            name = value;
            OnPropertyChanged();
        }
    }
}

